The energy required to ionize the atom from the ground state is given by
\begin{align*}
\Delta E&=13.6Z^2\text{ eV}\\
&=13.6Z^2\times1.6\times10^{-19}\text{ J}
\end{align*}
This energy must be provided by the photon. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\Delta E&=h\nu\\
&=\frac{hc}{\lambda}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \Delta E&=\frac{6.6\times10^{-34}\times3\times10^8}{0.1\times10^{-9}}\\
&=19.8\times10^{-17}\text{ J}
\end{align*}
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
19.8\times10^{-17}&=13.6Z^2\times1.6\times10^{-19}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad Z^2&=\frac{19.8\times10^{-17}}{13.6\times1.6\times10^{-19}}\\
&=8.97\\
\Rightarrow\qquad Z&=\boxed{3}
\end{align*}
The final answer is: $\boxed{3}$
